<emphasis id="E4D15575755AFFD5B0D06F3917F5E20F" bold="true" box="[151,435,1869,1896]" pageId="0" pageNumber="231">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755AFFD5B1596F3A17F5E20F" box="[286,435,1869,1895]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755AFFD5B1596F3A17F5E20F" bold="true" box="[286,435,1869,1895]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="231">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9EBFDAEC755AFFD4B0D06FE317A9E7A4" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="232" pageId="0" pageNumber="231" type="description">
<paragraph id="D61A8967755AFFD5B0D06FE31768E29D" blockId="0.[151,1437,1940,2037]" pageId="0" pageNumber="231">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755AFFD5B1536FE217DAE2C5" box="[276,412,1941,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755AFFD5B1536FE217DAE2C5" box="[276,412,1941,1965]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="231">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the Neotropical Region and before now included a single described species, 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755AFFD5B0D06FCE1443E2B9" authority="Lindner, 1949" authorityName="Lindner" authorityYear="1949" box="[151,517,1976,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulva">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755AFFD5B0D06FCE171BE2B9" box="[151,349,1977,2001]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="231">Arthropeina fulva</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755AFFD5B1236FCF1443E2B9" author="Lindner" box="[356,517,1976,2001]" pageId="0" pageNumber="231" refString="Lindner, E. (1949) Neotropische Stratiomyiiden des Britischen Museums in London. - Theil I. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 12, 1 (11), 782 - 821. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222934808653947" type="journal article" year="1949">
Lindner, 
<number id="606D9B40755AFFD5B18D6FCE1443E2B9" box="[458,517,1977,2001]" pageId="0" pageNumber="231" value="1949.0">1949</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The real diversity of the genus, however, is pretty large, as predicted by Woodley (2009, 2011).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D61A8967755BFFD4B08068E0137AE474" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">
Besides the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755BFFD4B21F68EF14F7E5D8" box="[600,689,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulva">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755BFFD4B21F68EF14F7E5D8" box="[600,689,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">A. fulva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B29868E015CBE5D8" author="Lindner" box="[735,909,151,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Lindner, E. (1949) Neotropische Stratiomyiiden des Britischen Museums in London. - Theil I. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 12, 1 (11), 782 - 821. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222934808653947" type="journal article" year="1949">
Lindner (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B30E68EF15C3E5D8" box="[841,901,152,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="1949.0">1949</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, subsequent papers have addressed the genus. 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B0D068CA179EE5BC" author="Papavero" box="[151,472,188,213]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Papavero, N. &amp; Artigas, J. N. (1991) Phylogeny of the American genera of Solvidae (Xylomyidae) (Diptera), with illustrations of the female spermatheca. Gayana Zoologia, 55 (2), 101 - 113." type="journal article" year="1991">
Papavero &amp; Artigas (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B1D168CB1796E5BC" box="[406,464,188,212]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
illustrated the female genitalia, including the spermatheca morphology. 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B57F68CB16A7E590" author="Woodley" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Woodley, N. E. (1999) Lectotype designations in Xylomyidae and Stratiomyidae (Diptera). Entomological News, 110 (4), 201 - 205." type="journal article" year="1999">
Woodley (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B0D86897169FE590" box="[159,217,224,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="1999.0">1999</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
made 
<typeStatus id="091E37C5755BFFD4B17A68A817E5E590" box="[317,419,223,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">lectotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="091E37C5755BFFD4B1AB68A814C5E590" box="[492,643,223,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">paralectotype</typeStatus>
designations for the 
<typeStatus id="091E37C5755BFFD4B3D768971586E590" box="[912,960,224,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">type</typeStatus>
material, while Woodley (2009, 2011) commented on the diagnosis of the genus within a phylogenetic discussion of the family (
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B4C569731376E474" author="Woodley" box="[1154,1328,260,285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Woodley, N. E. (2011) A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In: Thompson, F. C., Brake, I. &amp; Lonsdale, O. (Eds.), Contributions to the Biosystematic Database of World Diptera. Myia, 12, 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">
Woodley, 
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B4B269731376E474" box="[1269,1328,260,284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D61A8967755BFFD4B08069501788E754" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">
The recognition of the genus was largely based on body color—primarily yellow, sometimes with shining black maculae—and the shape of the two apical flagellomeres, which form a stylus. The shape of the stylus was considered autapomorphic for the genus (
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B233690715E3E4E0" author="Papavero" box="[628,933,367,392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Papavero, N. &amp; Artigas, J. N. (1991) Phylogeny of the American genera of Solvidae (Xylomyidae) (Diptera), with illustrations of the female spermatheca. Gayana Zoologia, 55 (2), 101 - 113." type="journal article" year="1991">
Papavero &amp; Artigas, 
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B32D690715E3E4E0" box="[874,933,368,392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B3F369181225E4E0" author="Woodley" box="[948,1123,367,392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Woodley, N. E. (2011) A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In: Thompson, F. C., Brake, I. &amp; Lonsdale, O. (Eds.), Contributions to the Biosystematic Database of World Diptera. Myia, 12, 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">
Woodley, 
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B46069071225E4E0" box="[1063,1123,368,392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B55369071705E4C4" author="Papavero" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Papavero, N. &amp; Artigas, J. N. (1991) Phylogeny of the American genera of Solvidae (Xylomyidae) (Diptera), with illustrations of the female spermatheca. Gayana Zoologia, 55 (2), 101 - 113." type="journal article" year="1991">
Papavero &amp; Artigas (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B14669E3177DE4C4" box="[257,315,404,428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
proposed that a helicoid spermathecae with three “layers” or coils was autapomorphic for 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755BFFD4B0D069CF1759E4B8" box="[151,287,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755BFFD4B0D069CF1759E4B8" box="[151,287,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This, however, was criticized by 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B2E069C01526E4B8" author="Woodley" box="[679,864,439,464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Woodley, N. E. (2011) A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In: Thompson, F. C., Brake, I. &amp; Lonsdale, O. (Eds.), Contributions to the Biosystematic Database of World Diptera. Myia, 12, 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">
Woodley (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B35B69CF151EE4B8" box="[796,856,440,464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, who commented that the blind duct illustrated by the former authors could be a sac ruptured during the preparation, not a derived condition, as proposed. A possible additional apomorphy mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B20D69881543E770" author="Woodley" box="[586,773,511,536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Woodley, N. E. (2011) A world catalog of the Xylomyidae (Insecta: Diptera) In: Thompson, F. C., Brake, I. &amp; Lonsdale, O. (Eds.), Contributions to the Biosystematic Database of World Diptera. Myia, 12, 417 - 453." type="journal article" year="2011">
Woodley (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B2846A7714BBE770" box="[707,765,512,536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
are the valves of the spermathecal ducts, illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="B234F496755BFFD4B0D06A52178CE754" author="Papavero" box="[151,458,548,573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" refString="Papavero, N. &amp; Artigas, J. N. (1991) Phylogeny of the American genera of Solvidae (Xylomyidae) (Diptera), with illustrations of the female spermatheca. Gayana Zoologia, 55 (2), 101 - 113." type="journal article" year="1991">
Papavero &amp; Artigas (
<number id="606D9B40755BFFD4B1C26A531787E754" box="[389,449,548,572]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D61A8967755BFFD4B0806A3017A9E7A4" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">
This paper reviews the genus 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755BFFD4B25E6A3F14E7E708" box="[537,673,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755BFFD4B25E6A3F14E7E708" box="[537,673,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, describing five new Neotropical species and redescribing 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755BFFD4B57A6A3F13D3E708" box="[1341,1429,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulva">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755BFFD4B57A6A3F13D3E708" box="[1341,1429,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">A. fulva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including illustrations of the antenna, palpus, thorax, spermatheca, genital fork, and male genitalia. The paper also adds some comments on the issue of the relationships within the genus and provides an identification key for the known species of 
<taxonomicName id="11A5F2E4755BFFD4B1276AC317AEE7A4" box="[352,488,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Xylomyidae" genus="Arthropeina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="232" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4D15575755BFFD4B1276AC317AEE7A4" box="[352,488,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="232">Arthropeina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
